TY  - JOUR
T1  - Optimal Cycle Times in Multistage Serial Systems with Set-Up and Inventory Costs
AU  - Karimi, Iftekhar A.
Y1  - 1992/10/01
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.38.10.1467
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.38.10.1467
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1467
EP  - 1481
VL  - 38
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Scheduling of multistage serial production systems under constant demand and infinite horizon is considered. The production stages operate with periodic shut-downs and startups. An integer nonlinear programming formulation is presented for determining a stationary, cyclic schedule with no stock-outs in any inventory and minimum sum of set-up and inventory costs. It allows a lot-sizing policy involving arbitrary, noninteger splitting/merging of lots. Three, almost optimal, heuristic algorithms and an exact branch and bound algorithm are developed using analytical results. Their evaluation using simulated problems shows the branch and bound algorithm to be the best, as it is fast even for systems with as many as 11 stages.
AB  - Scheduling of multistage serial production systems under constant demand and infinite horizon is considered. The production stages operate with periodic shut-downs and startups. An integer nonlinear programming formulation is presented for determining a stationary, cyclic schedule with no stock-outs in any inventory and minimum sum of set-up and inventory costs. It allows a lot-sizing policy involving arbitrary, noninteger splitting/merging of lots. Three, almost optimal, heuristic algorithms and an exact branch and bound algorithm are developed using analytical results. Their evaluation using simulated problems shows the branch and bound algorithm to be the best, as it is fast even for systems with as many as 11 stages.
